name: Ace of Spades
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: 'Ace of Spades' is considered one of the first and greatest speed-metal songs.

name: Alabama Getaway
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: This song appeared on the Grateful Dead album "Go to Heaven," whose cover marks the only known instance of the Dead in white disco suits.

name: Alex Chilton
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: 'Alex Chilton' is a salute to the frontman of Big Star, one of the ultimate indie-rock cult heroes. Chilton also sang for '60s hitmakers, the Box Tops.

name: Alive
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: Eddie Vedder wrote the lyrics to "Alive" after learning that the man he thought was his father was actually his stepfather. This revelation prompted a handful of Vedder's songs.

name: Almost Easy
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: 'Almost Easy' is the first Avenged Sevenfold song to include vocals by all five members of the band.

name: American Woman
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: What did the Guess Who have against American women anyway? According to guitarist Randy Bachman, it's an anti-war song and the "woman" is the Statue of Liberty.

name: Aqualung
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: Although Ian Anderson's flute is Jethro Tull's trademark, there isn't a note of flute playing on "Aqualung".

name: Bad Reputation
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: The line "I don't give a damn 'bout my reputation" usually gets a little saltier when Joan Jett sings it live.

name: Bodhisattva
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: In Buddhist teachings, a bodhisattva is any highly enlightened being.

name: Carry On Wayward Son
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: Kansas keyboardist Kerry Livgren, who wrote "Carry on Wayward Son," later became a big name in Christian rock.

name: Chop Suey!
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: The Ramones also have a song called "Chop Suey." Neither song is actually about chop suey.

name: Colony of Birchmen
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: The title "Colony of Birchmen" is a tribute to a Genesis epic, "Colony of Slippermen".

name: Come Out and Play (Keep 'Em Separated)
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: The Offspring's album Smash, which included "Come Out & Play," set a record as the biggest-selling album for a band on an indie label.

name: Cool for Cats
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: If you're wondering what the line about the Sweeney doing 90 means, "The Sweeney" was a hugely popular British crime show in the '70s.

name: Down with the Sickness
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: The violent mother/son dialogue in "Down with the Sickness" reportedly bothered a lot of parents and radio programmers, prompting the band to release a version without it.

name: Drain You
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: Instruments that appear in the bridge of "Drain You" include a rubber duck, chains and an aerosol can.

name: Eye of the Tiger
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: 'Eye of the Tiger' was written for the movie 'Rocky III'. But of course, you already knew that.

name: Feel the Pain
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: On "Feel the Pain," J Mascis became Dinosaur Jr.'s drummer as well as its singer, songwriter, guitarist and keyboardist.

name: Float On
album_name: Good News for People Who Love Bad News
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: Modest Mouse weren't the first group to have a hit single called "Float On." Soul and disco group The Floaters had one in 1977.

name: Give It All
album_name: Siren Song of the Counter Culture
author: Harmonix

name: Go Your Own Way
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: During the recording of the "Rumours" album, four Fleetwood Mac band members broke up with each other and drummer Mick Fleetwood divorced his wife.

name: Hello There
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: Cheap Trick still opens most of its concerts with "Hello There" and closes with "Goodnight Now".

name: I Was Wrong
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: The drummer on "I Was Wrong" is Deen Castronovo, who later became a member of Journey.

name: Kids in America
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: Both singers who scored a hit with "Kids in America" were named Kim. The original was performed by Kim Wilde, and The Muffs' Kim Shattuck performed it for the "Clueless" soundtrack.

name: Lazy Eye
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: Silversun Pickups named their album Carnavas after the maiden name of lead singer Brian Aubert's mom.

name: Let There Be Rock
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: AC/DC played their first American tour to promote the 1977 release of "Let There Be Rock." One of their stops was the New York punk mecca CBGB.

name: Livin' on a Prayer
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: After "Livin' on a Prayer," the characters Tommy and Gina appeared in at least two other Bon Jovi songs.

name: Lump
artist: The Presidents of the United States of America
album_name: The Presidents of the United States of America
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: The Presidents of the United States of America (or PUSA) are known for their unique modded guitars known as the guitbass and the basitar.

name: Master Exploder
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: 'Master Exploder' appears in Tenacious D's movie 'The Pick of Destiny' as they start their quest for the guitar pick that will give them rock supremacy.

name: Mountain Song
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: Though some fans didn't get the joke, Perry Farrell's stage name is a play on the word "peripheral." His real name is Peretz Bernstein.

name: My Own Worst Enemy
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: Pop star Avril Lavigne has done a cover version of "My Own Worst Enemy" in her live show.

name: One Way or Another
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: Blondie's bassist Nigel Harrison, who co-wrote "One Way Or Another" was the only Englishman in the lineup.

name: Painkiller
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: During the "Painkiller" tour, singer Rob Halford rode a motorcycle onstage and collided with a drum riser. He finished the show before going to the hospital.

name: Panic Attack
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: At eight minutes, "Panic Attack" is relatively short for a Dream Theater song. Their longer epics have run as long as 42 minutes.

name: Peace Sells
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: Soon after "Peace Sells" was released, leader Dave Mustaine fired half the band.

name: Pinball Wizard
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: Nobody has ever successfully played pinball by sense of smell. You could be the first.

name: Pretend We're Dead
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: This song, from L7's third album "Bricks Are Heavy," was produced by Butch Vig, who also did landmark Nirvana, Smashing Pumpkins and Sonic Youth albums in the same two-year stretch.

name: Psycho Killer
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: 'Psycho Killer' was David Byrne's attempt to describe what went on in a criminal's mind. He has said he got the idea from listening to a lot of Alice Cooper.

name: Ramblin' Man
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: Two different people who play on "Ramblin' Man" - Gregg Allman and guitarist Les Dudek - later dated Cher.

name: Round and Round
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: 'Round & Round' was covered live at least once by Metallica. They played it in Maryland during 1993.

name: Shooting Star
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: Paul Rodgers was inspired to write "Shooting Star" after the deaths of rock heroes Jimi Hendrix and Janis Joplin.

name: Spirit in the Sky
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: Norman Greenbaum's followup single to "Spirit in the Sky" was "Canned Ham," a song about... canned ham. It was not a hit.

name: Tangled Up in Blue
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: There are many layers of meaning in "Tangled Up in Blue." The shifts in perspective were partly inspired by painting classes that Dylan was taking at the time.

name: Teen Age Riot
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: According to the band, "Teen Age Riot" is about a vision of the future when Dinosaur Jr. leader J Mascis is elected President.

name: Testify
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: Part of the "Testify" lyrics were cribbed from George Orwell's "1984," a longtime inspiration for political rock songs.

name: The Middle
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: The lyrics of "The Middle" were the band cheering itself up after losing a record-label contract. The song helped get them a second one.

name: The Trees (Vault Edition)
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: Though Rush fans have found many deep meanings in "The Trees," drummer/lyricist Neil Peart has said it was inspired by a cartoon where trees acted like people.

name: Today
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: When he wrote "Today", Smashing Pumpkins' Billy Corgan was battling writer's block, feeling pressure to make a hit, fighting with his bandmembers, and breaking up with his girlfriend. Otherwise, things were great.

name: White Wedding (Part 1)
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: Billy Idol wrote "White Wedding" when his sister got married. Despite the song's menacing tone, his sister's marriage is still intact.

name: You Oughta Know
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: Before her American breakthrough with "You Oughta Know," Alanis Morissette made two dance-pop albums that were only released in Canada.

name: A Jagged Gorgeous Winter
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: The music video for "A Jagged Gorgeous Winter" was filmed in 4 hours in Vermont and edited in the van on the ride back to Boston.

name: Conventional Lover
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: Despite what you might infer from this song's lyrics, all four members of Speck have actually felt the touch of a woman. Different women, probably.

name: Supreme Girl
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: Supreme Girl is actually a reference to failed supreme court nominee Harriet Miers.

name: Visions
author: Harmonix
loading_phrase: Harmonix artist Mallika Sundaramurthy is the lead singer of Abnormality. Yup, that's a girl singing. For real.
